Why does std::set use a Red-Black Tree?****VVVVVIMP

A Red-Black Tree (RBT) is a self-balancing Binary Search Tree (BST). 
It keeps the tree approximately balanced after every insertion and deletion, ensuring efficient operations.

It provides:

Search: O(log n)
Insert: O(log n)
Delete: O(log n)

These are exactly the complexity guarantees required by the C++ Standard for std::set.

A Red-Black Tree is a self-balancing Binary Search Tree in which every node is assigned a color (Red or Black). 
The tree maintains a set of balancing rules so that its height remains O(log n), ensuring efficient search, insertion, and deletion.

Q2. Why not a normal BST?

A normal BST can become skewed:

10
 \
 20
  \
  30
   \
   40

Its height becomes O(n), making search, insertion, and deletion O(n).

Q3. Why not an AVL Tree?

AVL trees are more strictly balanced, so searches can be a little faster. 
However, they require more rotations during insertions and deletions. 
Red-Black Trees strike a good balance between lookup and update performance.

