19. How are duplicates detected in set?
----------------------------------------
set does NOT use operator==.

It uses the comparator (operator< by default).

Two objects are considered equivalent if:

!(a < b) && !(b < a)

Example:

Employee(1, "A")
Employee(1, "B")

If operator< compares only id, then both objects are considered equivalent and only one will be stored.

----------------------------------

20. Does insertion invalidate iterators?
-----------------------------------------
No.

Insertion into a set does NOT invalidate existing iterators.

Example:

set<int> s = {10,20};

auto it = s.find(10);

s.insert(30);

cout << *it;   // Still valid

Reason:
set is tree-based and does not reallocate memory like vector.

----------------------------------

21. When are set iterators invalidated?
----------------------------------------
Only when the pointed element itself is erased.

Example:

auto it = s.find(10);

s.erase(10);

Now 'it' becomes invalid.

Other iterators remain valid.

----------------------------------

22. How to get smallest and largest element?
--------------------------------------------

Smallest element:

*s.begin()

Largest element:

*prev(s.end())

Example:

set<int> s = {10,20,30};

cout << *s.begin();      // 10

cout << *prev(s.end());  // 30


