8. Iterator In set****
Why does set use Bidirectional Iterator?

Because std::set is implemented using a Red-Black Tree (balanced binary search tree).

Elements are NOT stored in contiguous memory like vector.

Example:

       5
      / \
     3   8
    / \
   1   4

Since data is stored as tree nodes:

✔ Move to next element  (++it)
✔ Move to previous element (--it)

But:

✘ it + 1
✘ it - 2
✘ it[5]

are not possible efficiently because there is no direct index access.

--------------------------------------------------

Advantage of Bidirectional Iterator

1. Can traverse both directions

for(auto it = s.begin(); it != s.end(); ++it)

for(auto it = prev(s.end()); ; --it)

2. Supports ordered containers

set, map, multiset, multimap remain sorted.

3. Efficient insert/delete

O(log n)

without invalidating most iterators.

--------------------------------------------------

Interview Answer

std::set provides a Bidirectional Iterator because it is implemented as a Red-Black Tree.
Tree nodes can efficiently move to the next or previous element, so ++ and -- are supported. 
Random access (it+1, it[5]) is not supported because elements are not stored in contiguous memory.
