********set on user defined objects******VVVVVIMP
Yes. std::set can store user-defined class objects, but it must know how to compare two objects because set keeps elements sorted.

Method 1: Overload operator< (Most Common)
#include <iostream>
#include <set>
using namespace std;

class Employee
{
public:
    int id;
    string name;

    Employee(int i, string n)
        : id(i), name(n) {}

    bool operator<(const Employee& other) const //******VVVVVVImp why build error if operator < is not const
    {
        return id < other.id;
    }
};

why build error if operator < is not const****VVVVVVIMP
The reason is that std::set stores its elements as const, so it can only call const member functions on them.
set<employee> s;

s.insert(employee("Pavan",23));
Internally, the Red-Black Tree stores const employee

