Method 2: Custom Comparator
class Employee
{
public:
    int id;
    string name;

    Employee(int i, string n)
        : id(i), name(n) {}
};

struct Compare
{
    bool operator()(const Employee& a,
                    const Employee& b) const
    {
        return a.id < b.id;
    }
};

set<Employee, Compare> s;

std::set can store user-defined objects.

Since set keeps elements sorted, it needs a way to compare objects.

This can be provided by:
1. Overloading operator<
2. Supplying a custom comparator

Internally, set uses the comparator to maintain ordering and determine uniqueness.

